  1. Copy the help file for runireg onto your text editor (>?runireg). Also copy code for runireg onto your text editor. The code, without comments, is listed by typing the runireg at the command prompt (>runireg)

  2. Add comments to the file as a programmer would to indicate the steps being carried out. There should be a comment for each line of code stating what is being computed.

my_runireg=function (y, X, betabar, A, nu, ssq) 
{
    n = length(y)   # define the number of observation
    k = ncol(X) # define the number of independent variable 
    RA = chol(A)    # cholesky decomposition of A=(RA)'(RA), RA is the upper                 
                  # triangular Cholesky root of A 
                    
    W = rbind(X, RA)    # W=(x,RA)' 
    z = c(y, as.vector(RA %*% betabar)) # x=(y,RA*betabar)'
    IR = backsolve(chol(crossprod(W)), diag(k)) # UL decomposition: W'W=R'R, 
                                #so solve(W'W)=(IR)*t(IR)
    btilde = crossprod(t(IR)) %*% crossprod(W, z)   # compute inv(W'W)*W'z. 
                           
    res = z - W %*% btilde   # compute the residual.
    s = t(res) %*% res       # compute the SSE. 
    sigmasq = (nu * ssq + s)/rchisq(1, nu + n)  # draw sigmasq from 
#Inverted Chi-square 
            
    beta = btilde + as.vector(sqrt(sigmasq)) * IR %*% rnorm(k)  
# draw beta from multivariate normal 
                       
    list(beta = beta, sigmasq = sigmasq)    # list the output variables
}

  1. Write your own R code to sample from the prior distribution. An easy way to do this is to use some of the lines of code in your file hw2_reg.R. Consider the standard diffuse prior: ^2~(_0 s_02)/(_(_0)2 ) _0=3; s_02=1 |2~N(0,^2 A^(-1) ) A=.01I_(dim()
library(MASS)
set.seed(123)
k = 3 ## Number of independent parameters (beta0,beta1,beta2)
nu =3 ## As given in the question
ssq = 1 ## As given in the question
R=100 ## Number of obsevations to be generated 
A=diag(rep(0.01,k)) ## Diagonal matrix of dimension k=3. The diagonal elements are 0.1. 
betabar=rep(0,k) ## Zero vector of dimensions equal to the number of independent parameters.

 

beta=array(double(R*k),dim=c(R,k)) ## defining an empty RXk array to be updated later. 
sigmasq=array(double(R),dim=c(R)) ## defining an empty vector to be updated later

for (rep in 1:R) {
    # draw sigmasq from Inverted Chi-square with nu degrees of freedom. 
    sigmasq[rep] = (nu * ssq)/rchisq(1, nu)  ## given in the formula
    
    ## Given that we know sigmasq, beta follows a multivariate normal distribution with mean = zero vector (beta bar) (dim = 3X1) and variance-cov matrix = sigmasq X Ainverse (dim=3X3). 
    
    # draw beta from multivariate normal
    cov=sigmasq[rep]*solve(A) ## defining the var-covariance matrix. Solve used to calculate inverse of A. 
    root=chol(cov) 
    beta[rep,]=betabar+root%*%rnorm(k)  ## Sampling from a multivariate normal distribution with betabar as the mean vector and cov as the var-covariance matrix.   
   
}

draws=cbind(beta,sigmasq)
boxplot(data.frame(draws))

  1. Write your own R code to simulate a dataset of 100 observations from the following regression model by selecting a value of and sigma2. The design matrix X contains an intercept and two independent variables.
## for prior A = 0.01
n=100
X=cbind(rep(1,n),runif(n),runif(n)) ## Design matrix with intercept term as well. 
## selecting a beta vector and the corresponding sigmasq from the ones generated in ques4)

beta_vector = beta[1,]
sigmasq_selected = draws[1,4] 

y_vector = X%*%beta_vector + rnorm(n,sd=sqrt(sigmasq_selected)) ## vector of 100 observations

Get posterior draw

betai=c(1,1,1)
sigsqi=3.0

Data<-list(y=y_vector,X=X)
Prior<-list(betabar=betabar,A=A,nu=nu,ssq=ssq) 
Initial<-list(beta=betai,sigsq=sigsqi)
Mcmc<-list(R=2000,keep=10) 

y=Data$y
X=Data$X 

n = length(y)       
k = ncol(X)     

betabar=Prior$betabar
A=Prior$A 
nu=Prior$nu
ssq=Prior$ssq

oldbeta=Initial$beta
oldsigsq=Initial$sigsq 

R=Mcmc$R 
keep=Mcmc$keep 

betadraw=array(double(floor(R/keep)*k),dim=c(floor(R/keep),k))
sigsqdraw=array(double(floor(R/keep)),dim=c(floor(R/keep)))  

for (rep in 1:R){
  
  #==============
  # draw sigmasq
  #==============
  sse=crossprod((y-X%*%oldbeta))
  oldsigsq = (nu * ssq + sse)/rchisq(1, nu + n)
  oldsigsq=oldsigsq[1,1] # redefine oldsiqsq as a scalar
  
  
  #=======================
  # draw beta
  #=======================
  avar=(1/oldsigsq)*(t(X)%*%X)+A 
  avar=chol2inv(chol(avar))
  amean=(1/oldsigsq)*(t(X)%*%y)+A%*%betabar
  amean=avar%*%amean
  root=chol(avar)
  oldbeta=amean+root%*%rnorm(k)
  
  
  
  #==============
  # save draws 
  #==============
  
  if(rep%%keep ==0){
    mkeep=rep/keep
    betadraw[mkeep,]=oldbeta
    sigsqdraw[mkeep]=oldsigsq 
  }
  
  list(betadraw = betadraw, sigsqdraw = sigsqdraw)
  
} # end of rep-loop
